00:29:29,514 --> 00:29:31,771
What do you want?
Why are you in my house?

493
00:29:31,896 --> 00:29:34,345
I work for the district
attorney's office.

494
00:29:36,628 --> 00:29:38,179
I want to help you.

495
00:29:41,052 --> 00:29:42,989
- I don't need any help.
- Yes, you do.

496
00:29:43,114 --> 00:29:45,615
- You could be tried for murder.
- I don't think so,

497
00:29:45,785 --> 00:29:48,369
'cause all those people you keep
talking about, they killed themselves.

498
00:29:48,537 --> 00:29:50,584
No, they decided to end
their lives quickly

499
00:29:50,709 --> 00:29:53,526
rather than face the slow death
you were threatening.

500
00:29:53,651 --> 00:29:54,959
Can you prove that?

501
00:30:01,724 --> 00:30:03,300
I'm offering you a way out.

502
00:30:04,439 --> 00:30:06,429
Come with me
to the district attorney's office.

503
00:30:06,875 --> 00:30:08,843
We will explain what happened.

504
00:30:09,472 --> 00:30:11,953
How you started hearing
Cooper's voice in your head.

505
00:30:12,078 --> 00:30:15,062
How your mom tried to get you treatment
and medication, but it didn't work.

506
00:30:16,047 --> 00:30:17,597
You're still a minor.

507
00:30:18,403 --> 00:30:20,403
The court will show you mercy.

508
00:30:21,345 --> 00:30:22,345
Mercy?

509
00:30:25,797 --> 00:30:27,697
They should give me a medal.

510
00:30:28,710 --> 00:30:30,619
Do you know how many lives
I've saved?

511
00:30:30,960 --> 00:30:33,493
I go to school,
I look at all the other kids.

512
00:30:33,618 --> 00:30:36,016
The captain of the team,
the girl who stars in all the plays,

513
00:30:36,141 --> 00:30:37,883
and they're like the overachievers,

514
00:30:38,008 --> 00:30:40,572
the ones who get in all the good
colleges, that everybody talks about.

515
00:30:40,697 --> 00:30:43,051
What have they done?
Played a game, sang a song?

516
00:30:43,176 --> 00:30:44,383
Look at what I do.

517
00:30:45,262 --> 00:30:47,344
All the people in
that diner were going to die.

518
00:30:47,512 --> 00:30:50,210
All the patients that woman cared for,
she was gonna kill.

519
00:30:50,335 --> 00:30:53,017
- And you're gonna stop us? Why?
- Because it's wrong.

520
00:30:53,185 --> 00:30:54,573
But it's not wrong!

521
00:31:02,398 --> 00:31:03,498
You know... 

522
00:31:04,867 --> 00:31:08,063
When he first started appearing
to me, I would ignore him,

523
00:31:08,852 --> 00:31:10,410
pretend I couldn't see.

524
00:31:11,663 --> 00:31:14,263
He was screaming at me about
this guy in Scottsdale.

525
00:31:14,841 --> 00:31:16,868
Said he was depressed
and was gonna take his .38

526
00:31:16,993 --> 00:31:20,279
and shoot his wife and two kids right
before he blew his own brains out.

527
00:31:20,962 --> 00:31:23,606
Agent Cooper asked me if
I would do something about it.

528
00:31:23,731 --> 00:31:27,396
He said he'd show me how to get in
the house, what to say, what to do.

529
00:31:29,056 --> 00:31:30,429
I just ignored him.

530
00:31:32,191 --> 00:31:34,613
The next day, I wake up,
my mom's watching the news.

531
00:31:34,738 --> 00:31:37,018
"Murder-suicide in Scottsdale."
Some guy snaps,

532
00:31:37,188 --> 00:31:38,792
kills his whole family.

533
00:31:39,894 --> 00:31:41,480
I could have saved them.

534
00:31:41,959 --> 00:31:42,775
No.

535
00:31:46,038 --> 00:31:47,154
You know I'm right.

536
00:31:47,566 --> 00:31:49,322
- No, I don't.
- It's like he always says,

537
00:31:49,492 --> 00:31:51,107
"Just do the math."

538
00:31:52,209 --> 00:31:54,353
You kill one guilty person,
you save two innocent ones.

539
00:31:54,478 --> 00:31:56,192
You kill 20, you save a hundred.

540
00:31:56,317 --> 00:31:58,641
You kill a hundred,
you save a thousand.

541
00:31:59,358 --> 00:32:01,176
- Do the math.
- This isn't math!

542
00:32:02,125 --> 00:32:03,700
This is something else.

543
00:32:03,825 --> 00:32:06,090
It's vigilantism, and it's wrong.

544
00:32:06,434 --> 00:32:07,434
No,

545
00:32:08,421 --> 00:32:09,421
it isn't.

546
00:32:11,187 --> 00:32:12,846
It's really kind of perfect.

547
00:32:14,795 --> 00:32:17,152
Anyway, you're gonna have to leave.
I have...

548
00:32:17,769 --> 00:32:18,769
homework.

549
00:32:24,405 --> 00:32:26,078
Honey, you coming to bed?

550
00:32:27,813 --> 00:32:28,813
Someday.

551
00:32:30,267 --> 00:32:31,609
What if you can't do it?

552
00:32:31,734 --> 00:32:34,397
What if you can't come up with
a solution that improves on Hal's?

553
00:32:34,522 --> 00:32:37,173
Don't say that.
Don't even put that out there.

554
00:32:40,934 --> 00:32:44,658
Maybe I should just surrender
and get used to the fact that Hal...

555
00:32:44,783 --> 00:32:46,259
thieving, slimy,

556
00:32:46,875 --> 00:32:49,458
untrustworthy Hal is someone
I'm going to just have to see

557
00:32:49,583 --> 00:32:51,428
every day of my professional life.

558
00:32:51,904 --> 00:32:54,989
When and if he chooses
to come into the office, that is.

559
00:32:56,935 --> 00:32:59,085
You all right if I stay
out here for a bit?

560
00:32:59,210 --> 00:33:00,610
I'll see you soon.

561
00:33:04,465 --> 00:33:05,465
Daddy?

562
00:33:06,686 --> 00:33:08,036
- Daddy?
- Yeah.

563
00:33:10,149 --> 00:33:13,016
Ariel, what'd you... what's going on?
Everything all right?

564
00:33:13,552 --> 00:33:14,852
What time is it?

565
00:33:14,977 --> 00:33:17,663
- Oh, God. What are you doing up?
- I don't know.

566
00:33:18,455 --> 00:33:20,396
It's like midnight or something.

567
00:33:21,859 --> 00:33:24,207
I had another dream
about that Clay guy.

568
00:33:24,332 --> 00:33:25,961
He wanted me to tell you something.

569
00:33:26,920 --> 00:33:28,130
Oh you did? What?

570
00:33:28,638 --> 00:33:31,216
He wants you to look at something
called the Mellinger Equation.

571
00:33:31,557 --> 00:33:33,107
"Mellinger Equation"?

572
00:33:33,877 --> 00:33:36,027
- Do you mean Mallinger?
- Yeah.

573
00:33:36,833 --> 00:33:38,858
He says you're supposed to "apply

574
00:33:39,205 --> 00:33:43,016
"1-ethyl-3 and then extrapolate it
from four vectors".

575
00:33:43,141 --> 00:33:44,141
What?

576
00:33:44,561 --> 00:33:45,975
He kept screaming it at me,

577
00:33:46,100 --> 00:33:48,436
until I promised I'd wake up
and write it down.

578
00:33:56,800 --> 00:33:57,800
Why?

579
00:33:59,570 --> 00:34:01,747
Why did you leave?

580
00:34:16,388 --> 00:34:18,665
I just got off the phone
with the hospital again.

581
00:34:18,790 --> 00:34:21,600
For the moment at least,
he's... he's still hanging on.

582
00:34:22,533 --> 00:34:23,826
I'll keep you posted.

583
00:34:23,951 --> 00:34:25,299
I appreciate that.

584
00:34:26,315 --> 00:34:29,795
It was in front of us the whole time,
Terry. We just didn't see it.

585
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:31,360
The Mallinger Equation.

586
00:34:32,014 --> 00:34:35,207
It really does solve all of
our dye sensitizer problems.

587
00:34:36,314 --> 00:34:39,934
The key is applying it
to a lighter photosensitive material,

588
00:34:40,059 --> 00:34:43,265
and then applying Mallinger
to four additional surface vectors,

589
00:34:43,390 --> 00:34:46,451
thereby reducing the amount of
external sensitization that's required.

590
00:34:46,576 --> 00:34:49,982
Thereby reducing
our material costs by... what?

591
00:34:50,107 --> 00:34:51,717
Three, maybe four percent?

592
00:34:51,842 --> 00:34:53,674
It might even go so high as five.

593
00:34:56,854 --> 00:34:58,354
What can I say, Joe?

594
00:34:59,483 --> 00:35:03,487
I guess I underestimated just how much
you dislike working with Hal Munzell.

595
00:35:03,942 --> 00:35:05,867
Are you on board with this?

596
00:35:07,360 --> 00:35:09,503
I'm a man of my word, Joe.

597
00:35:11,456 --> 00:35:12,856
Consider him gone.

598
00:35:14,005 --> 00:35:17,705
Well, if he ever comes back in the
office, I'll be sure to let him know.

599
00:35:18,099 --> 00:35:19,241
That's great, Joe.

600
00:35:19,980 --> 00:35:23,229
Well, I guess sometimes things do
work out the way they're supposed to.

601
00:35:24,984 --> 00:35:26,554
Soon, I hope.

602
00:35:26,986 --> 00:35:30,024
They're still operating.
Devalos and I are just waiting.

603
00:35:33,647 --> 00:35:34,832
Joe, I gotta go.

604
00:35:34,957 --> 00:35:36,998
Tell the girls
I'll be home in a bit.

605
00:35:41,559 --> 00:35:43,015
Douglas Reilly just expired.

606
00:35:59,102 --> 00:36:02,605
"Dear Joe, I made a decision
to end my life tonight..."

607
00:36:02,876 --> 00:36:04,594
Hello again, Mrs. Dubois.

608
00:36:06,854 --> 00:36:08,507
Nice note, don't you think?

609
00:36:08,807 --> 00:36:10,699
I'm going to need you to sign that.

610
00:36:10,824 --> 00:36:12,697
By the way, I'm have a gun
in my left hand

611
00:36:12,822 --> 00:36:15,749
which is pointed directly
at the center of your spine.

612
00:36:16,260 --> 00:36:17,955
A single bullet
at this close proximity,

613
00:36:18,080 --> 00:36:20,067
even through the rear of your seat,

614
00:36:20,192 --> 00:36:22,147
should disable
but not kill you immediately,

615
00:36:22,272 --> 00:36:24,072
causing unimaginable pain.

616
00:36:25,431 --> 00:36:27,920
- Brandon, don't do this.
- Sign the note,

617
00:36:28,411 --> 00:36:30,920
put the key in the ignition
and drive to the roof.

618
00:36:47,882 --> 00:36:51,708
There are video cameras all over this
lot. You're being recorded right now.

619
00:36:52,173 --> 00:36:54,273
Not tonight.
The system's down.

620
00:36:55,036 --> 00:36:56,689
Will be
until it's serviced tomorrow.

621
00:36:56,814 --> 00:36:59,611
Agent Cooper is very thorough.
You ought to know that by now.

622
00:36:59,736 --> 00:37:02,177
Agent Cooper?
This was his idea?

623
00:37:03,123 --> 00:37:04,669
Our work is very important.

624
00:37:04,794 --> 00:37:06,979
We can't let you get in the way.

625
00:37:07,104 --> 00:37:09,704
Now, I'm going to need you
to climb up on that wall.

626
00:37:10,209 --> 00:37:13,021
- I can't do that, Brandon.
- I think you will.

627
00:37:13,765 --> 00:37:16,179
You're going to climb up on that wall,
and jump off it,

628
00:37:16,304 --> 00:37:18,861
'cause if you don't,
I will shoot you, Mrs. Dubois.

629
00:37:24,360 --> 00:37:25,951
You're going to have to shoot me.

630
00:37:30,088 --> 00:37:31,460
What's the matter?

631
00:37:32,534 --> 00:37:34,620
Didn't Cooper tell
you this might happen?

632
00:37:34,745 --> 00:37:37,016
No he didn't, did he?
'Cause he didn't know.

633
00:37:37,141 --> 00:37:39,422
Just like he didn't know
about Douglas Reilly.

634
00:37:42,501 --> 00:37:44,140
Who... who's Douglas Reilly?

635
00:37:45,426 --> 00:37:46,835
I'm going to get...

636
00:37:51,586 --> 00:37:53,617
Douglas Reilly is a man who...

637
00:37:53,742 --> 00:37:55,885
actually did commit suicide
last night,

638
00:37:56,010 --> 00:37:58,760
and not because anybody
was threatening him,

639
00:37:59,970 --> 00:38:01,920
but because he lost his wife,

640
00:38:02,451 --> 00:38:06,121
and he couldn't imagine spending
another day without her.

641
00:38:07,057 --> 00:38:08,057
See him?

642
00:38:09,857 --> 00:38:12,107
His wife's name was Rachel Stetson.

643
00:38:20,774 --> 00:38:24,009
His wife was a killer.
So, it's like Cooper says. Do the math.

644
00:38:24,327 --> 00:38:26,082
No, no, no. You do the math.

645
00:38:26,763 --> 00:38:29,303
His wife hadn't killed anybody.

646
00:38:30,256 --> 00:38:31,699
Anybody. Not yet.

647
00:38:31,824 --> 00:38:34,520
And I'm starting to think
she probably never would have.

648
00:38:36,297 --> 00:38:37,955
Wait a second.
What are you saying?

649
00:38:38,080 --> 00:38:40,524
I'm saying, honey,
the future isn't fixed.

650
00:38:40,649 --> 00:38:42,643
It isn't certain.
It is fluid.

651
00:38:43,196 --> 00:38:44,296
Agent Cooper

652
00:38:44,563 --> 00:38:48,241
couldn't have known that Rachel Stetson
was going to kill all those people.

653
00:38:48,737 --> 00:38:51,147
Or that somebody wouldn't
have discovered her.

654
00:38:51,272 --> 00:38:53,776
Or that she wouldn't have
had a change of heart.

655
00:38:53,901 --> 00:38:55,623
Any more he could
have been certain that

656
00:38:55,793 --> 00:38:59,714
Adam Dietz was going to walk into
that diner and blow everyone away.

657
00:39:00,621 --> 00:39:03,360
Who's to say that somebody
wouldn't have stopped him?

658
00:39:03,485 --> 00:39:06,417
Who's to say that he wouldn't
have stopped himself?

659
00:39:09,531 --> 00:39:11,214
No, he saw it.
He, he knew it.

660
00:39:11,339 --> 00:39:13,684
He was certain of it.
He even said you dreamt about it.

661
00:39:14,092 --> 00:39:15,079
I did.

662
00:39:15,204 --> 00:39:16,204
I did.

663
00:39:16,757 --> 00:39:19,587
My dreams are always,
always fooling with me.

664
00:39:19,712 --> 00:39:21,770
You can... you can call my husband.

665
00:39:22,427 --> 00:39:25,429
- Call the people I work with.
- So what are you saying?

666
00:39:25,554 --> 00:39:26,655
I'm saying...

667
00:39:27,191 --> 00:39:29,275
do the math, Brandon.

668
00:39:30,624 --> 00:39:32,074
Cooper's using you.

669
00:39:32,905 --> 00:39:36,289
He wants you to think
that he's infallible, but he isn't.

670
00:39:38,084 --> 00:39:39,084
I am never

671
00:39:39,820 --> 00:39:41,253
gonna jump off that wall.

672
00:39:43,187 --> 00:39:44,673
So, you're gonna have to kill me.

673
00:39:47,475 --> 00:39:48,675
Or better yet,

674
00:39:49,669 --> 00:39:50,995
give me that gun.

675
00:39:51,841 --> 00:39:54,444
Give me the gun,
we're going to get back in the car,

676
00:39:54,569 --> 00:39:56,219
we'll drive downstairs,

677
00:39:56,344 --> 00:39:57,633
we'll talk to my boss.

678
00:39:57,758 --> 00:40:00,480
That's just not an option,
Mrs. Dubois.

679
00:40:01,601 --> 00:40:03,350
We don't have much time.
Pull the trigger.

680
00:40:03,475 --> 00:40:06,054
We'll drive the car away,
leave her here,

681
00:40:06,179 --> 00:40:07,738
make it look like a carjacking.

682
00:40:07,906 --> 00:40:09,447
Is what she's saying right?

683
00:40:09,833 --> 00:40:13,837
Is it possible I forced those people
to kill themselves for no reason at all?

684
00:40:13,962 --> 00:40:15,824
It's highly unlikely, Brandon.

685
00:40:16,359 --> 00:40:20,363
And we could hardly afford to wait
and just let awful things happen.

686
00:40:20,735 --> 00:40:22,544
That would've defeated
our entire purpose.

687
00:40:24,751 --> 00:40:25,964
Now pull the trigger.

688
00:40:26,132 --> 00:40:27,841
You said she was going to jump!

689
00:40:28,180 --> 00:40:29,738
Give me the gun, Brandon.

690
00:40:29,863 --> 00:40:31,463
If you don't kill her,

691
00:40:31,940 --> 00:40:33,135
she will arrest you.

692
00:40:33,260 --> 00:40:36,058
- And you will go to prison.
- I told you, we'll go talk to my boss.

693
00:40:36,226 --> 00:40:39,227
I believe that he will recommend
that the court show you mercy.

694
00:40:39,395 --> 00:40:41,306
I wouldn't count on mercy, son.

695
00:40:41,829 --> 00:40:44,191
You've already had a hand
in the deaths of three people.

696
00:40:47,028 --> 00:40:48,195
Now pull the trigger!

697
00:40:51,963 --> 00:40:53,075
There you go.

698
00:40:54,569 --> 00:40:55,569
Don't.

699
00:40:56,381 --> 00:40:58,439
Now, do what you have to do.

700
00:41:00,148 --> 00:41:02,971
There's no reason to feel doubt

701
00:41:03,096 --> 00:41:04,795
or uncertainty, Brandon.

702
00:41:07,815 --> 00:41:09,151
He is using you.

703
00:41:10,322 --> 00:41:11,635
None of this is your fault.

704
00:41:12,704 --> 00:41:14,507
Don't listen to her, Brandon.

705
00:41:16,305 --> 00:41:18,023
What we're doing is right.

706
00:41:18,736 --> 00:41:20,838
We're making the world better.

707
00:41:21,813 --> 00:41:22,863
You'll see.

708
00:41:23,930 --> 00:41:27,854
Once you've actually pulled
that trigger, everything will change.

709
00:41:28,690 --> 00:41:30,290
You'll feel wonderful.

710
00:41:33,781 --> 00:41:35,450
- What are you doing?!
- Brandon, no!

711
00:41:42,843 --> 00:41:44,343
Where have you been?

712
00:41:44,468 --> 00:41:46,242
I've been worried about you.

713
00:41:46,505 --> 00:41:47,949
First I was at...

714
00:41:48,074 --> 00:41:50,568
at the hospital.
And then I was talking to this...

715
00:41:50,693 --> 00:41:52,093
this boy's mother.

